metadata.name: Perpetual Oscillations  #37
metadata.description:
Planes expand and contract over time in different rhythms. 

Display notes:
The work is intended to be viewed running live in the browser, and there is no set aspect ratio. The viewer is invited to explore the space and choose their viewpoint. 

Controls:
Left-clicking and dragging - rotate around the center 
right-clicking and dragging - pan around the space 
Scrolling - zoom in and out 
Press b - b-side 
Press o - go back to the origin 
Press 1 to 3 - change the pixel density
Adjusting pixel density or changing the screen size will bring you back to the origin. 

License: CC BY-NC-ND 4.0

Made with p5.js

metadata.name: Mudaashiku #187
metadata.description:
Mudaashiku (「無駄足区」- “Fool’s Errand District”) invokes the place where you first really experienced what it means to be a person in a city. Were you awestruck? Did you feel lost or disoriented by a realization of the size of the spaces around you? Perhaps you sought some detail, some small thing to focus on to reorient yourself and feel like a person again in the face of such immensity and confusion.

This work is inspired by an attempt to capture some of the feeling I had when I first moved to Tokyo and was utterly overwhelmed. It was both exciting and frightening to suddenly be lost in a place so immense and unfamiliar. If Stendhal Syndrome refers to the fearful ecstasy of experiencing the beauties of Florence, then there must be something similar for the first experience of a great city. This work attempts only to point in the direction of such a feeling.

Take a moment to experience the district as a whole, but then, with a change of perception, your focus may shift to the individual building or group of buildings. And then, back again. This duality of scales has been integral to the development of the work.

The work expresses eight features:
Aspect ratio: 1:1.2, 1:1.41, 1.41:1, 1.2:1
Environment: Central (most common), north river, east river, south causeway, west causeway (most rare).
Palette: Thirty seven selected palettes. Chosen either for their aesthetic qualities, or as an attempted expression of some element of urban life.
Divisions: 15, 18, or 21.
Color variance: 0.03, 0.06, 0.09, 0.12, 0.18, 0.27, 0.36, 0.54.
Sun direction: East or west.
Locale: Either central or commuter town. Determines the height profile of the district.
Roads: Represented, or not.

The work begins by gradually revealing the layout of the district. This process can take from about 6 seconds to as much as 2 minutes, but 50 to 60 seconds is typical. When this process is complete, the colors and facades will be added and the work revealed.

Once the work is complete, it can be adjusted using the following controls:

[0] Fit size to window (default)
[1] Set shortest edge to 1000 pixels
[2] Set shortest edge to 2000 pixels
[3] Set shortest edge to 4000 pixels
[4] Set shortest edge to 8000 pixels (please be patient!)

After changing the dimensions, the work may appear the same size in your browser. The new dimensions will be apparent when you save an image.

[s] Save work at current dimensions
[b] Add or remove border
[g] Add or remove background grain

Made in 100% vanilla javascript.
OpenSimplexNoise.js used for noise.

metadata.name: Reaching #44
metadata.description:
Reach for the stars.

However impossible it may seem, there's always a way. As long as you believe.
Everybody has a way to their stars, and the only way to reach it is to try as hard as you can and believe in yourself. I will forever live by this and believe in it.

A couple of the palettes used in this piece were adapted from the ever great Studio Yorktown, thank you for providing these incredible combinations of colors :)

--

Press spacebar or right click to save an image.

--

Reaching is a piece I dedicate to my recently passed grandmother. Rest in piece, we love you and miss you.

metadata.name: Ecce Gratum #31
metadata.description:
"Ecce Gratum" is a symphony of colors and lines, a visual work that sings to the soul. The strokes of the brush are bold and confident, yet gentle and loving, like the notes of a symphony. The title, "Ecce Gratum", translates to "Behold the pleasing", and as you gaze upon this art, it is impossible not to be moved by its beauty and wonder. This painting is a celebration of life, a reminder to embrace the present and to find joy in the simple things. It is a call to look beyond the surface, to see the beauty in the world around us, and to let our hearts sing

[S] on live view to save a png

metadata.name: Primordial #95
metadata.description:
Primordial is a study of abstract forms. The algorithm, written in p5.js and WebGL, utilizes domain warping to create twisted fields of color and then overlays thousands of tiny lines to provide depth and texture. The outputs are chaotic but not completely formless, like a swirling mass of plasma from the early universe, or a strange proto-life form suspended in prehistoric ooze.

CONTROLS:

1-9: Increase resolution and save image in PNG format

B: Toggle borders on/off

F: Fullscreen
P: Portrait
L: Landscape
S: Square

For third party license information, please see license.md

David Brice Allen
October 2022

metadata.name: plottable_pumpkins #9
metadata.description:
Happy Spooky Season everyone!

This is a fun little date-night project I worked on. The mission: create some decorations to put up for Halloween. In the time it took me to make this (~3 hours, with experimentation), my talented wife managed to make several much more beautiful handmade decorations. However, now, I can make infinite adequate jack-o-lanterns with no effort. This is the essence of programming 😆

Some notes about this piece:

- press "s" to save an svg of your pumpkin
- it's meant to be plotted and then cut. plot the black lines, and cut the white lines
- if anyone actually carves one, please let me know on whatever social media you're using, find me at https://aebrer.xyz

metadata.name: Temporality #35
metadata.description:
temporality
/ˌtɛmpəˈralɪti/
The state of existing within or having some relationship with time.

Inspired by the patterns and textures formed where land meets water. Swirling river banks, sedimentary plains, estuaries and deltas - sometimes formed in minutes or hours, other times over hundreds of years.

Temporality explores the ideas of impermanence and erosion and the inevitability of change.

As Philip K. Dick writes in A Scanner Darkly:

"Everything in life is just for a while"

Read the accompanying fxtext article for more details on how this collection came about.

= = = = = = = = =

Press [1] to display @ 1400 x 2100 (default)
Press [2] to display @ 4200 x 6300
Press [S] to download the current resolution

metadata.name: As the Wind Blows #408
metadata.description:
As the leaves slowly fall...floating through the winds of winter. A fresh scent wafts through the air, and with it comes youthful memories of hopping on the school bus, waving back at your parents, and staring out the classroom window.

Dreams and the memories of life are never motionless—just as the wind never stops blowing.


Controls:
Double-click to resize the Sketch to your window.
Press S to save a copy of the sketch.

Written in p5js, showcasing the blessings of nature.
Created by Alex and Andrew Mitchell in Autumn 2023

metadata.name: Fragment Assembler #100
metadata.description:
Fragment Assembler is a chaos engine that creates complex abstract patterns and textures. As the artwork is drawn, it constantly recomposes itself during assembly with a series of displacement techniques, creating new forms and visual elements, while others get broken into pieces and textures. The work is orientation agnostic, and will display the output in portrait orientation on tall displays.

Intended to display on high resolution mode. The artwork renders with lower resolution by default to maintain compatibility with lower end devices. 

Press '2' to double the internal resolution (recommended).
Press 'h' to enable full internal resolution (requires a modern desktop computer).
Press space bar to reload the work.
Press 's' to save the output as PNG.
To render a 6k PNG, first press 'h', then save with 'p' (requires a modern desktop computer).


Made with p5.js & WebGL.
Best displayed with a modern desktop system & Chrome browser. 


Licensed under CC BY-NC-SA 4.0

metadata.name: Not so iso #247
metadata.description:
Isometric and Glitch, order and chaos, two apparently incompatible art forms, two completely different worlds, two types of art that I love.
This collection aims to combine these two styles without distorting them.

Press 'S' to download.
